'''{{ill|Kotoshironushi Shrine|ja|事代主神社|qq=draft}}''' (ことしろぬしじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Nitakubi|ja|似首郷|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shinkamigotō, Nagasaki|ja|新上五島町|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|qq=draft}}.
== Enshrined Deities == The shrine enshrines four deities: * {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔男神|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|qq=draft}} (worshiped as [[Konpira Gongen|Konpira]])
Among them, {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔男神|qq=draft}} was enshrined following the merger with {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社|qq=draft}}.
== History == [[File:IMG_nitakubi2.JPG|170px|thumb|Worship Hall]] [[File:IMG_nitakubi1.JPG|170px|thumb|Ebisu Shrine]]
The shrine was founded in Bunmei 15 (1483) on September 15. Historically, the region has practiced {{ill|phallus worship|ja|性器崇拝|qq=draft}}, with tall, protruding rocks resembling male genitalia considered sacred. Behind the shrine, {{ill|Ebisu Shrine|ja|恵美須神社|qq=draft}} enshrines stones shaped like male genitalia.
In Meiwa 8 (1771), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, and {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft}} (worshipped as {{ill|Ebisu|ja|恵美須神|qq=draft}}) was invited from {{ill|Nishinomiya Shrine|ja|西宮神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|qq=draft}}. The shrine likely adopted the name {{ill|Ebisu Shrine|ja|恵美須神社|qq=draft}} around this time. The shrine buildings were washed away by waves in Bunka 3 (1806), later rebuilt, but burned down in Bunkyū 1 (1862).
In Meiji 3 (1870), the shrine was renamed Kotoshironushi Shrine. In Meiji 7 (1874), it was designated as a {{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft}}. In Meiji 41 (1908), it merged with Yasaka Shrine. The shrine burned down again in Shōwa 8 (1933), but was designated as a {{ill|Shinsen Heihaku-ryō Kyōshin Shrine|ja|神饌幣帛料供進神社|qq=draft}} in Shōwa 9 (1934).
== Festivals == The {{ill|Gion Festival|ja|祇園祭|qq=draft}} and the annual festival on October 18–19 feature performances of {{ill|Kamigoto Kagura|ja|上五島神楽|qq=draft}}. This kagura was designated as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|無形民俗文化財|qq=draft}} in 1981 and later as a national {{ill|Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|選択無形民俗文化財|qq=draft}} in 2002.<ref>[https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/137114 Cultural Heritage Online]</ref> In 2016, it was designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft}} of Japan.<ref>[http://www.pref.nagasaki.jp/bunkadb/index.php/view/459 Nagasaki Prefecture Cultural Properties]</ref>
;Major Festivals and Rituals * {{ill|Gantan-sai (New Year's Festival)|ja|元旦祭|qq=draft}} (January) * Dragon God Festival (March) * {{ill|Water God Festival|ja|水神祭|qq=draft}} (April) * Nagoshi Festival (June) * {{ill|Gion Festival|ja|祇園祭|qq=draft}} (July) * {{ill|Reisai|fr|Reisai|lt=Annual Grand Festival|ja|例大祭|qq=draft}} (October 18–19) * {{ill|Shichi-Go-San Festival|ja|七五三祭|qq=draft}} (November) * {{ill|Ōharae (Great Purification Ceremony)|ja|大祓式|qq=draft}} (December)
== Nearby Shrines == Other shrines in Nitakubi include: * {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|qq=draft}}
Nearby districts also have shrines: * {{ill|Maruo Shrine|ja|丸尾神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Maruo|ja|丸尾郷|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Masahiko Shrine|ja|政彦神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Nama|ja|奈摩郷|qq=draft}}
<gallery> File:IMG_maruo.JPG|{{ill|Maruo Shrine|ja|丸尾神社|qq=draft}} (Maruo) File:IMG_nama.JPG|{{ill|Masahiko Shrine|ja|政彦神社|qq=draft}} (Nama) </gallery>
