{{Shrine | name = {{ill|Kotoshironushi Shrine|ja|事代主神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi Shrine|qq=}} | image = [[File:IMG_nitakubi.JPG|250px]] | location = {{ill|Shinkamigotō, Nagasaki|ja|新上五島町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinkamigotō, Nagasaki|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagasaki Prefecture|qq=}}, Nitakubi 806 | coordinates = {{coord|33|01|08.4|N|129|05|29.8|E|scale:25000|name=Kotoshironushi Shrine}} | deity = {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|qq=}} and three other deities | status = Former Village shrine | established = Bunmei 15 (1483) | main_hall = | festival = October 19 | rituals = {{ill|Kamigoto Kagura|ja|上五島神楽|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamigoto Kagura|qq=}} (Gion Festival, Annual Grand Festival) }}
'''{{ill|Kotoshironushi Shrine|ja|事代主神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi Shrine|qq=}}''' (ことしろぬしじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Nitakubi|ja|似首郷|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitakubi|qq=}}, {{ill|Shinkamigotō, Nagasaki|ja|新上五島町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinkamigotō, Nagasaki|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagasaki Prefecture|qq=}}.
== Enshrined Deities == The shrine enshrines four deities: * {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|qq=}} * {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=}} * {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔男神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} * {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmononushi|qq=}} (worshiped as [[Konpira Gongen|Konpira]])
Among them, {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔男神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} was enshrined following the merger with {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasaka Shrine|qq=}}.
== History == [[File:IMG_nitakubi2.JPG|170px|thumb|Worship Hall]] [[File:IMG_nitakubi1.JPG|170px|thumb|Ebisu Shrine]]
The shrine was founded in Bunmei 15 (1483) on September 15. Historically, the region has practiced {{ill|phallus worship|ja|性器崇拝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/phallus worship|qq=}}, with tall, protruding rocks resembling male genitalia considered sacred. Behind the shrine, {{ill|Ebisu Shrine|ja|恵美須神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebisu Shrine|qq=}} enshrines stones shaped like male genitalia.
In Meiwa 8 (1771), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, and {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|qq=}} (worshipped as {{ill|Ebisu|ja|恵美須神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebisu|qq=}}) was invited from {{ill|Nishinomiya Shrine|ja|西宮神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishinomiya Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Settsu Province|qq=}}. The shrine likely adopted the name {{ill|Ebisu Shrine|ja|恵美須神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebisu Shrine|qq=}} around this time. The shrine buildings were washed away by waves in Bunka 3 (1806), later rebuilt, but burned down in Bunkyū 1 (1862).
In Meiji 3 (1870), the shrine was renamed Kotoshironushi Shrine. In Meiji 7 (1874), it was designated as a {{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/village shrine|qq=}}. In Meiji 41 (1908), it merged with Yasaka Shrine. The shrine burned down again in Shōwa 8 (1933), but was designated as a {{ill|Shinsen Heihaku-ryō Kyōshin Shrine|ja|神饌幣帛料供進神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen Heihaku-ryō Kyōshin Shrine|qq=}} in Shōwa 9 (1934).
== Festivals == The {{ill|Gion Matsuri|lt=Gion Matsuri|lt=Gion Festival|ja|祇園祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Festival|1=Gion and Tenno Festivals|lt=Gion Festival|2=ja|3=祇園祭|4=zh|5=祇園祭|6=fr|7=Festivals de Gion et Tenno|8=es|9=Festivales de Gion y Tenno|10=ru|11=Фестивали Гион и Тэнно|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Festival|qq=}} and the annual festival on October 18–19 feature performances of {{ill|Kamigoto Kagura|ja|上五島神楽|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamigoto Kagura|qq=}}. This kagura was designated as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Nagasaki Prefecture|qq=}} in 1981 and later as a national {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Intangible Folk Cultural Properties Requiring Documentation|lt=Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|選択無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} in 2002.<ref>[https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/137114 Cultural Heritage Online]</ref> In 2016, it was designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} of Japan.<ref>[http://www.pref.nagasaki.jp/bunkadb/index.php/view/459 Nagasaki Prefecture Cultural Properties]</ref>
